"Risk factor" includes any of the following factors that an infant may display and are considered relevant in determining the possibility of a hearing impairment:
An admission for more than 48 hours to a neonatal intensive care nursery;
An anatomical malformation that involves the head or neck, including:
A dysmorphic appearance;
A morphologic abnormality of the pinna;
An overt or submucous cleft palate; and
Any syndromal or nonsyndromal abnormality;
A severe asphyxia, including:
An infant with an Apgar score of 0-3 who fails to institute spontaneous respiration within 10 minutes; or
An infant with hypotonia that persists during the 1st 2 hours of the infant's life;
A bacterial meningitis, especially H. influenza;
A birth weight of less than 1500 grams;
A congenital perinatal infection, including cytomegalovirus, herpes, rubella, syphilis, and toxoplasmosis;
A family history of a childhood hearing impairment; and
A hyperbilirubinemia at a level that exceeds indications for exchange transfusion.
